<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920108-0042</DOCNO><DOCID>920108-0042.</DOCID><HL>   MCI Adds Incentives   For Callers Who Cease   Using Rivals' Cards</HL><DATE>01/08/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   MCIC</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>LONG DISTANCE TELEPHONE PROVIDERS (LDS)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><NS>NEW PRODUCTS andamp; SERVICES (PDT)</NS><RE>DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA (DC)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- MCI Communications Corp. unveiled newcalling-card services and an offer of discounts on calls tocustomers who stop using rivals' cards.   With the new card, MCI is offering these customers about$35 worth (or four hours) of free calls, MCI said. Inaddition, customers will have access to advanced phoneservices such as voice mail, speed dialing, conferencecalling and a message service that will deliver a customer'sprerecorded message to another party. All of these, exceptthe speed-dialing service, command a fat fee, however.</LP><TEXT>   Calling-card customers of MCI can set up a conference callby dialing an &quot;800&quot; number and by paying $2.50 for eachnumber connected to the conference. The MCI Messenger servicewill deliver a card member's message for $1.60 per message.   MCI's new service aims to lure away additional customersof American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co. and rival US SprintCommunications Co., a unit of United Telecommunications Inc.A sales promotion begun by MCI last summer to sign up thefriends and families of its customers in return for 20%calling discounts has lured several million customers awayfrom ATandamp;T, according to analysts. ATandamp;T disputed this, sayingits market share has remained stable and that its cardservices are competitive. Sprint noted that it was first tooffer conference calling to card customers and that it willbring out additional card services in coming months.</TEXT></DOC>